<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8" />
  <title>{{ title }}</title>
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />
</head>
<body>
<header>
  <h1>{{ title }}</h1>
  <p>
    URL: <code>{{ schema_url }}</code>
  </p>
</header>

<main>
  <section>
    <h2>Summary</h2>
    <p>
      This page is the specification (the "contract") for the response
      returned by the CBRWS v1 discovery endpoint,
      <code>{{ api_url }}</code>. It describes exactly what fields that
      response contains, what they mean, and what other URLs the
      response links to. (In this documentation the word
      <em>endpoint</em> means a URL that responds to HTTP requests; the
      two terms are used interchangeably.)
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Where This Page Fits</h2>
    <p>
      This page lives inside <code>/profiles</code> in the URL
      hierarchy of this web service:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <code>/profiles</code> &mdash; the top-level index of every
        schema family on this server.
      </li>
      <li>
        <code>/profiles/cbrws</code> &mdash;
        <a href="{{ cbrws_directory_url }}">parent directory</a>,
        listing the versions of the CBRWS schema that this server
        publishes.
      </li>
      <li>
        <code>/profiles/cbrws/v1</code> &mdash;
        <strong>this page</strong>. The v1 API specification.
      </li>
      <li>
        <code>/profiles/cbrws/v1/rels/</code> &mdash;
        <a href="{{ relations_directory_url }}">relations directory</a>.
        It has a sub-page for every custom link relation this API uses
        (see the <a href="#link-relations">Custom Link Relations</a>
        section below).
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      The path prefix <code>/profiles/</code> reflects a term from the
      HTTP standard RFC 6906, which calls this kind of specification a
      <em>profile</em>. In this documentation and in the rest of the
      codebase we use the word <em>schema</em> for the same idea; the
      URL path keeps the older name.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Background: Terms Used on This Page</h2>
    <p>
      The sections below use several terms from HTTP and REST
      standards. If you already know them, skip ahead to
      <a href="#response-contract">The /api Response Contract</a>.
      Otherwise, here is a short glossary.
    </p>
    <dl>
      <dt><em>JSON Schema</em></dt>
      <dd>
        A JSON document that formally describes the shape of another
        JSON document &mdash; the fields it contains, their types, and
        which are required. A client can feed it to a JSON Schema
        validator library to check automatically that a response is
        well-formed. The machine-readable version of this page (fetched
        with <code>Accept: application/schema+json</code>) is a JSON
        Schema for the <code>{{ api_url }}</code> response.
      </dd>
      <dt><em>HAL</em> (Hypertext Application Language)</dt>
      <dd>
        A lightweight convention for embedding navigation links inside
        a JSON response. Links go under a top-level key named
        <code>_links</code>; the rest of the document is ordinary JSON.
        The CBRWS API serves its responses as HAL+JSON
        (<code>{{ api_media_type }}</code>).
      </dd>
      <dt><em>Link relation</em></dt>
      <dd>
        A short name attached to a link that describes how the linked
        resource relates to the current one &mdash; for example
        <code>self</code> (the current resource's own URL),
        <code>up</code> (its parent), or a custom name like
        <code>cbrws:greeting</code>. The HAL document puts these names
        as keys inside the <code>_links</code> object.
      </dd>
      <dt><em>CURIE</em> (Compact URI)</dt>
      <dd>
        A shorthand for long URIs. HAL lets an API define its own link
        relations, but the names are supposed to be URIs, which are
        verbose. A CURIE lets the API declare a prefix
        (<code>cbrws:</code>) that expands into a longer URL template.
        In this API, <code>cbrws:greeting</code> expands to
        <code>{{ greeting_relation_url }}</code> &mdash; the
        documentation page for that relation.
      </dd>
      <dt>The HTTP <code>profile</code> link relation</dt>
      <dd>
        A standard link-relation name defined in RFC 6906. It points to
        a document that describes the contract a response follows.
        Inside a HAL link object, it is also carried as the
        <code>profile</code> member. CBRWS uses it to point clients at
        this specification page.
      </dd>
    </dl>
  </section>

  <section id="response-contract">
    <h2>The /api Response Contract</h2>
    <p>
      A response from <code>{{ api_url }}</code> is a JSON object with
      the following top-level fields:
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Field</th>
          <th>Type</th>
          <th>Required</th>
          <th>Description</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>title</code></td>
          <td>string</td>
          <td>Yes</td>
          <td>Display name of the API (e.g. "CBRWS API").</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>version</code></td>
          <td>string</td>
          <td>Yes</td>
          <td>
            Version string for the CBRWS schema that the response
            conforms to (e.g. "1.0").
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>description</code></td>
          <td>string</td>
          <td>No</td>
          <td>Optional human-readable description of the API.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>_links</code></td>
          <td>object</td>
          <td>Yes</td>
          <td>HAL link collection &mdash; see below.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>The <code>_links</code> Object</h3>
    <p>
      The <code>_links</code> object must contain the following members:
    </p>

    <h4><code>self</code></h4>
    <p>A link pointing at <code>{{ api_url }}</code> itself.</p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Member</th>
          <th>Type</th>
          <th>Required</th>
          <th>Description</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>href</code></td>
          <td>URI</td>
          <td>Yes</td>
          <td>Absolute URL of the discovery endpoint.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>type</code></td>
          <td>string</td>
          <td>Yes</td>
          <td>
            Media type of the response
            (<code>{{ api_media_type }}</code>).
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>profile</code></td>
          <td>URI</td>
          <td>Yes</td>
          <td>
            The URL of this specification page
            (<code>{{ schema_url }}</code>).
          </td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h4><code>curies</code></h4>
    <p>
      An array declaring the CURIE prefixes used elsewhere in
      <code>_links</code>. For the CBRWS API, this array contains one
      entry binding the prefix <code>cbrws:</code> to the relations
      directory.
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Member</th>
          <th>Type</th>
          <th>Required</th>
          <th>Description</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>name</code></td>
          <td>string</td>
          <td>Yes</td>
          <td>
            Prefix used in link-relation names (always <code>cbrws</code>
            for this API).
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>href</code></td>
          <td>URI template</td>
          <td>Yes</td>
          <td>
            Template that expands to a relation's documentation URL.
            Always ends in <code>/{rel}</code>.
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>templated</code></td>
          <td>boolean</td>
          <td>Yes</td>
          <td>
            Always <code>true</code>, signalling that <code>href</code>
            contains a <code>{rel}</code> placeholder that clients must
            substitute.
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>type</code></td>
          <td>string</td>
          <td>No</td>
          <td>
            Optional. Hint about what content negotiation will return
            when a client dereferences the expanded URL.
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>profile</code></td>
          <td>URI</td>
          <td>No</td>
          <td>Optional.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>
      To expand a CURIE, replace <code>{rel}</code> in the template
      with the part of the relation name that follows the colon. For
      example, <code>cbrws:greeting</code> expands to
      <code>{{ greeting_relation_url }}</code>.
    </p>

    <h4 id="link-relations">Custom Link Relations</h4>
    <p>
      Every custom link relation below is documented on its own page
      under the relations directory,
      <code>{{ relations_directory_url }}</code>. Clients do not need
      to follow these links to call the API &mdash; they are a
      machine-readable way for a client to discover what each relation
      means.
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Relation</th>
          <th>Target URL</th>
          <th>Documentation</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>cbrws:greeting</code></td>
          <td><code>{{ greeting_url }}</code></td>
          <td>
            <a href="{{ greeting_relation_url }}">Greeting relation page</a>
          </td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>
      Each relation's link object has the same three members as
      <code>self</code>: <code>href</code>, <code>type</code>, and
      <code>profile</code>. The relation's documentation page gives the
      exact expected values.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Example Response</h2>
    <p>
      A valid response from <code>{{ api_url }}</code> looks like this:
    </p>
    <pre><code>GET {{ api_url }}
Accept: {{ api_media_type }}

HTTP/1.1 200 OK
Content-Type: {{ api_media_type }}

{
  "title": "CBRWS API",
  "version": "1.0",
  "description": "This is the API endpoint for the cbrws web service.",
  "_links": {
    "self": {
      "href": "{{ api_url }}",
      "type": "{{ api_media_type }}",
      "profile": "{{ schema_url }}"
    },
    "curies": [
      {
        "name": "cbrws",
        "href": "{{ curie_href_template }}",
        "templated": true
      }
    ],
    "cbrws:greeting": {
      "href": "{{ greeting_url }}",
      "type": "{{ api_media_type }}",
      "profile": "{{ greeting_relation_url }}"
    }
  }
}</code></pre>
    <p>
      A client can validate this body against the JSON Schema returned
      by this same URL when the client sends
      <code>Accept: application/schema+json</code>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Content Negotiation</h2>
    <p>
      This specification page is available in two formats. Which one
      you receive depends on the <code>Accept</code> header in your
      request:
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th><code>Accept</code> Header</th>
          <th>What You Get</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>text/html</code> (or a browser)</td>
          <td>This human-readable page.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>
            <code>application/schema+json</code> (or omitted)
          </td>
          <td>
            A JSON Schema document that formally describes the
            <code>{{ api_url }}</code> response shape.
          </td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>Examples using curl:</p>
    <pre><code># Fetch the human-readable HTML page
curl -s -H "Accept: text/html" {{ schema_url }}

# Fetch the machine-readable JSON Schema
curl -s -H "Accept: application/schema+json" {{ schema_url }}</code></pre>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Compliance Checklist</h2>
    <p>
      A response from <code>{{ api_url }}</code> conforms to this
      specification if and only if:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        It is a JSON object containing <code>title</code>,
        <code>version</code>, and <code>_links</code>.
      </li>
      <li>
        <code>_links.self</code> contains <code>href</code>,
        <code>type</code>, and <code>profile</code>.
      </li>
      <li>
        <code>_links.curies</code> is an array whose first element sets
        <code>name</code>, <code>href</code> (with a <code>{rel}</code>
        placeholder), and <code>templated=true</code>.
      </li>
      <li>
        <code>_links["cbrws:greeting"]</code> contains
        <code>href</code>, <code>type</code>, and <code>profile</code>.
      </li>
      <li>
        Each CURIE expands to a URL under the relations directory, and
        dereferencing that URL returns documentation or a JSON Schema
        via content negotiation.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>
</main>

